(numbers do not count for everything.  [The commentator here\015)'
(quotes Sun Tzu, V. SS. 5, 6 and 10.]  Now the rebels have pitched\015)'
(their camp in the midst of thick grass which will easily burn\015)'
(when the wind blows.  If we set fire to it at night, they will be\015)'
(thrown into a panic, and we can make a sortie and attack them on\015)'
(all sides at once, thus emulating the achievement of T`ien Tan.'\015)'
([See p. 90.]  That same evening, a strong breeze sprang up;  so\015)'
(Huang-fu Sung instructed his soldiers to bind reeds together into\015)'
(torches and mount guard on the city walls, after which he sent\015)'
(out a band of daring men, who stealthily made their way through\015)'
(the lines and started the fire with loud shouts and yells.\015)'
(Simultaneously, a glare of light shot up from the city walls, and\015)'
(Huang-fu Sung,  sounding his drums, led a rapid charge,  which\015)'
(threw the rebels into confusion and put them to headlong flight."\015)'
([HOU HAN SHU, ch. 71.] ]\015)'
